INSERT INTO `pi_wiki_notes` VALUES (1249,1688,'<p>Just as our Earth, the Moon has been the object of study for geologists. To study Geology of the Moon, scientists use Earth telescopes, Lunar satellites, and <b>Moon rock samples</b>.<br/>The goal of this inquiry is to work with three examples of Moon rock samples.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Moon rock samples have been obtained in three different ways: </p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><p><b>Moon meteorites</b> ejected from the Moon and fell on Earth. About 120 lunar meteorites have been collected on Earth.</p></li>\r\n<li><p>Samples collected by the <b>Luna program</b>. The spacecrafts of this unmanned space program collected about 320 grams of Moon rock.</p></li> \r\n<li><p>Samples collected by the <b>Apollo program</b>. Apollo astronauts picked up rock samples in every mission that landed on the Moon. In total, 2.514 samples were collected. That\'s 382 kg of Moon rock!<br/>You can imagine collecting rocks from the Moon is not an easy task. In this clip you can see footage of astronauts Gene Cernan and Harrison Schmitt collecting samples during Apollo 17. This mission brought back to Earth more than 100kg of rock samples!</p>\r\n\r\n<iframe width=\"320\" height=\"180\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/evTLKNdgz88\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\r\n\r\n</li>  \r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>To investigate the rocks, some of the samples have been sliced, so that they can be studied under the microscope. Due to their rarity, Moon rock samples are invaluable, so the slices can only be handled by experts with the utmost care.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, this does not mean that we cannot access the samples: they have been digitalized. They can be seen using a Virtual Microscope software, which runs in modern web browsers. In this inquiry, you will use this Virtual Microscope to study three instances of rock samples.</p>\r\n'),(1262,1703,'<p>Here you can think about what it is you will investigate and type in your decisions.</p>\r\n\r\n         <table>\r\n         <tr>\r\n         <td><center><iframe src=\"http://projects.kmi.open.ac.uk/microscope/sections/78235/\" width=\"300px\"></iframe><br /><h2>Sample A</h2></center></td>\r\n         <td><center><iframe src=\"http://projects.kmi.open.ac.uk/microscope/sections/70181/\" width=\"300px\"></iframe><br /><h2>Sample B</h2></center></td>\r\n         <td><center><iframe src=\"http://projects.kmi.open.ac.uk/microscope/sections/14503/\" width=\"300px\"></iframe><br /><h2>Sample C</h2></center></td>\r\n         </tr>\r\n         </table>\r\n\r\n'),(1416,1956,'<p>When studying rocks and minerals, both from Earth or the Moon, geologists use a set of measures that help them collect and organize their data.<br/>\r\nIn this inquiry, you will use some of the most common measures.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Read this activity carefully in order to understand the types of data that you can record.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Measures to identify where you find data or relevant features:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><p><b>Rock sample</b>: This is simply the selection of the Moon rock for which you are collecting data.<br/>When you make a measurement (for instance, the size of a grain in a rock), use the <b>Rock sample</b> to specify the rock in which the measure was made.</p></li> \r\n<li><b>Sample snapshot</b>: This complement Rock sample. A <b>Sample snapshot</b> is a close-up view of the precise point in a Rock sample where you found your data. <br/>\r\nThis is useful when you want to review your data, and to provide prove of your data. When you collect new data, don\'t forget to select the right snapshot!</li></p>\r\n\r\n</ul>\r\n<li>Measures to collect data:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><p><b>Grain size</b>: This is a measurement, in millimeters, of the diameter of a grain that you have found within a Sample.\r\n<br/>Within the same sample you may find grain of different size. If you want to collect them, use the Snapshot measure to record where each measure was made.</p></li>\r\n<li><p><b>Color</b>: This is relevant a color that you identify in a sample. Geologists use a set of names of colors useful to describe features of samples.<br/>You must select a color from the provided list.</p></li> \r\n<li><p><b>Opacity</b>: The slices that you can see here are 30 microns thick (0.030 millimeters). Thanks to this, we can distinguish between transparent minerals, which allow light to traverse then, <br/>\r\nand opaque minerals, which appear as black since no light passes through them.</p></li>\r\n<li><p><b>Relief</b>: This is a term used to describe how much a mineral stands out. When a mineral under the microscope looks almost blank, we can say it has low relief. <br/>\r\nOn the other hand, other minerals show many features on their surface, indicating a high relief. </p></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n \r\n<p>Remember that a rock sample may display different features in different positions. Therefore you may take different measures of each sample, to record this variations.<br/>\r\nFor this purpose, using the snapshots is specially useful, as they will let you got back later to the position of a sample where you found relevant data.</p>\r\n'),(1419,1961,'my notes...fff'),(1421,1963,'These are my notesfff'),(1422,1964,'asfdasdf fdaasdf as'),(1423,1966,'sdgf');
